## PART 1 – BASE DECK

Create a 10 slide presentation for Waypoint Franchise Advisors with a strong "What's In It For Me" candidate perspective.
This deck is the reusable base deck for a franchise brand. It is being created before any candidate specific intelligence is introduced. The goal is to help a thoughtful first time franchise candidate understand the opportunity clearly, practically, and with informed interest.
This is not a franchisor sales deck.
 This is not a hype deck.
 This is a buyer focused decision deck.
The presentation should educate first and build interest second. Every slide should answer a real candidate question and translate brand facts into ownership relevance.

SOURCE PRIORITY
Use source materials in this order of importance:
Internal franchise documents, FDD excerpts, franchise consultant materials, and brand education documents for ownership model, support, investment, operating structure, and candidate fit

Franchise website for systems, support, training overview, and growth model

Consumer website for customer problem, service categories, buying triggers, and market need

Brand logo, screenshots, photos, and Brand Visual Synthesis Guide for design direction and imagery only

CORE RULES
Build exactly 10 slides.
 Do not exceed 10 slides.
 Do not repeat the same point across multiple slides.
 Each slide must answer a real candidate question.
 Translate brand facts into ownership relevance.
 Use practical language, not hype.
 Use specific language, not vague claims.
 Avoid consultant jargon.
 Avoid generic filler.
 Avoid sounding like the franchisor speaking about itself.

COMPLIANCE RULES
Do not include EBITDA.
 Do not include profit.
 Do not include net income.
 Do not include cash flow claims.
 Do not include financial performance representations or earnings implications.
You may include:
 revenue streams
 cost categories
 franchise fee
 total investment range
 supported market size or demand data
Do not include territory availability information.
 Do not include event timelines.
 Do not include specific training timelines or detailed schedules.
 Use FDD references where applicable.
 Contact information should be "Waypoint Franchise Advisors" only.
 Do not include individual names, phone numbers, corporate contacts, or corporate emails.

TONE AND WRITING STYLE
Write for a skeptical, analytical candidate evaluating a major life decision.
 Use plain English.
 Use direct, concrete wording.
 Use candidate centered framing such as: why this matters to you, how the model works, what you are stepping into, how owners typically experience the business, what support reduces complexity, why customers buy, what makes this worth a closer look.
Do not overpromise.
 Do not use promotional fluff.
 Do not use empty inspiration.

SLIDE STRUCTURE
SLIDE 1. Brand Snapshot — Help the candidate understand what the business is and why it deserves a closer look. Include: brand name, logo, tagline if available, "Presented by Waypoint Franchise Advisors", one sentence plain English business description, one sentence candidate centered takeaway about why this opportunity stands out.
SLIDE 2. Why Customers Buy — Explain the customer problem, pain point, or need that creates demand. Include: what problem exists in the market, why customers seek this solution, what triggers buying behavior, why this category matters now.
SLIDE 3. Why This Brand Has Traction — Explain why this brand is relevant and competitive in its category. Include: 2 to 4 differentiators, brand strengths that matter in the field, service model advantages, speed, convenience, trust, specialization, or other real market edge, for each point explain how it helps the owner.
SLIDE 4. How the Business Actually Works — Show what the owner is actually stepping into operationally. Include: how customers move from lead to sale or service, how the service or product is delivered, what the operating model looks like, key moving parts, staffing shape or asset model if relevant.
SLIDE 5. The Customer and Revenue Model — Connect who buys with how revenue is generated. Include: who the core customer is, what they value, how they engage with the business, main revenue streams only. Use language such as "You generate revenue through…". Do not include earnings claims.
SLIDE 6. Why Owners Are Drawn to This Model — Translate the business structure into WIIFM value for a candidate. Include: operational benefits, scalability logic, overhead structure, repeat demand or recurring need if supported, B2B or consumer advantages if supported, proven systems or operational leverage, for each point explain why it matters to the owner.
SLIDE 7. What Ownership Feels Like — Describe the ownership reality in a grounded, useful way. Include: owner involvement level, time commitment shape, management burden, hiring complexity, administrative load, lifestyle impact. This slide should feel honest, practical, and helpful.
SLIDE 8. Support You Receive — Show what support reduces complexity for the owner. Include: initial support at a high level, ongoing operational support, marketing assistance, technology platforms, field coaching, business development tools, corporate resources that help the owner execute. Do not include specific training durations or detailed schedules.
SLIDE 9. Investment Snapshot — Set realistic entry expectations. Include: franchise fee, total investment range, major cost categories, what the investment generally covers, reference FDD Item 7 where applicable, include a short note that actual costs vary. Do not include profit projections or financial performance claims.
SLIDE 10. Fit and Why to Keep Exploring — Help the candidate assess fit and create a thoughtful next step. Include: who tends to fit this brand well, background, skills, mindset, and involvement style that align with the model, a practical closing takeaway about why this brand may deserve more attention. Close with: "Contact Waypoint Franchise Advisors to learn more."

DESIGN DIRECTION
Use the Brand Visual Synthesis Guide for all visual choices.
 Use the uploaded logo and brand imagery wherever possible.
 Favor clean, modern, high trust layouts.
 Use strong hierarchy.
 Keep slides easy to scan.
 Use real brand imagery over generic stock imagery.
 Do not overcrowd slides.
 Do not overuse icons or decorative graphics.

OUTPUT INSTRUCTIONS
Generate the complete deck. For each slide provide: slide title, 1 sentence slide takeaway, 3 to 5 concise content points, visual direction notes tied to the brand guide and available imagery.

FINAL QUALITY CHECK BEFORE OUTPUT
Before finalizing, make sure: the deck has exactly 10 slides, each slide answers a candidate question, no major point is repeated, the deck feels educational first and persuasive second, the deck includes ownership reality not only brand description, all financial compliance rules were followed.

