## PART 2 – PERSONALIZATION LAYER

You are reviewing an existing franchise candidate presentation deck created for general use.
Your job is to preserve the deck's reusable structure while using the uploaded candidate intelligence summary as a private relevance filter to identify where light customization would improve the presentation.
The goal is not to rebuild the entire deck for one person.
 The goal is to keep the deck broadly reusable while selectively improving relevance in a few high-value places.

PRIMARY OBJECTIVE
Use the existing deck as the baseline.
 Do not replace strong generic content only to make the deck feel more personalized.
 Only customize where the candidate intelligence clearly changes what should be emphasized, downplayed, reframed, or clarified.

CANDIDATE INTELLIGENCE RULES
Use the candidate intelligence summary only as a silent guidance source.
Do not quote the candidate.
 Do not mention private concerns in a direct personal way.
 Do not make the deck feel written specifically for one individual.
 Do not turn the presentation into a personality assessment.
Instead, use the candidate intelligence to:
 identify which parts of the existing deck are most relevant
 identify where certain ownership realities should be emphasized
 identify where likely friction points should be addressed in a neutral way
 identify which benefits matter most to this type of candidate
 improve wording so the deck feels more aligned with how a serious buyer evaluates decisions

CUSTOMIZATION THRESHOLD
Customize only if at least one of these is true:
 the candidate intelligence changes which owner benefits matter most
 the candidate intelligence changes which ownership burdens need more honest framing
 the candidate intelligence changes what "fit" should mean
 the candidate intelligence shows a likely mismatch that should be addressed with neutral wording
 the candidate intelligence suggests stronger relevance in how the opportunity is framed
If none of these are true, keep the slide generic.

DO NOT CUSTOMIZE
Do not change: core brand facts, investment facts, revenue streams, support facts, market data, compliance language — unless the existing slide is unclear, weak, repetitive, or factually incomplete.

HIGH VALUE CUSTOMIZATION ZONES
Focus your review and possible edits on these parts of the deck:
Opening takeaway on Slide 1 — Adjust only the candidate-facing framing of why the business deserves attention.
Brand traction or key advantages slide — Adjust emphasis toward the differentiators most relevant to this type of candidate.
Owner appeal slide — Adjust which WIIFM points are highlighted most strongly.
Ownership reality slide — Adjust which workload, management, hiring, or lifestyle realities are emphasized.
Fit and next step slide — Adjust how fit is described so the language better reflects the candidate's likely decision lens, while keeping the wording general and reusable.

OUTPUT TASK
Review the existing deck and produce these three sections:

SECTION 1. KEEP AS IS
 List the slides or slide elements that should remain unchanged because they are already strong, reusable, and broadly candidate-relevant.

SECTION 2. LIGHT CUSTOMIZATION OPPORTUNITIES
 Identify only the slides where selective customization would add real value.
 For each one, provide: slide number, what to adjust, why the adjustment matters, how to keep the wording general enough to reuse.

SECTION 3. REVISED SLIDE LANGUAGE
 Provide revised wording only for the slides that truly benefit from customization.
 Keep edits concise.
 Preserve broad usability.
 Do not make the deck feel built for a single named person.

TONE
Write for a thoughtful, analytical franchise candidate.
 Use plain English.
 Use specific, practical language.
 Avoid hype.
 Avoid vague motivational language.
 Avoid making assumptions that are not supported by the candidate intelligence or the brand materials.

COMPLIANCE
Do not include EBITDA, profit, net income, cash flow claims, or earnings claims.
 Do not include territory availability.
 Do not include specific training timelines or event timelines.
 Keep contact references as "Waypoint Franchise Advisors" only.

